    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-12-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-12-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="1095"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1095">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">662.11241/47</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-12-09">December 9,
                            1929</date>.<lb/>[Received December 27.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 5142</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In continuation of my despatch No. 4504, dated
                    April 29, 1929, I have the honor to enclose for the Department’s information
                    copy in translation of a decree<note n="92" xml:id="d1095fn92">Not
                        printed.</note> granting exemption for the payment of customs duties and
                    internal taxes to foreign consular officers stationed in Germany, provided
                    reciprocity is granted by the appointing State, transmitted to the Embassy by
                    the German Foreign Office.</p>
                <p>With reference to the Department’s telegraphic instruction No. 25, dated April
                    12, 3 p.m., 1926, authorizing the Embassy to insist on full reciprocity for
                    American consular officers assigned to Germany in importing effects and
                    merchandise free of duty at any time, the Embassy has the honor to request the
                    Department’s authorization to inform the Foreign Office that the reciprocity is
                    granted to German consular officers in the United States and that the
                    authorization be sent by cablegram in order to assist American consular officers
                    in Germany in receiving their Christmas packages.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Jacob Gould Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
